Analyzing Video Game Sales - Tom Dai¶

Video games have become a popular form of entertainment and a significant industry in recent years. According to industry reports, the global video game market was valued at over $175 billion in 2020, and it is projected to continue growing in the coming years.

The creation of video games have become more and more complex as both technolgy advances and consumer tastes change. This means that the development costs for one game is often atronomical, and today modern videogames often require millions of dollar funding similar to hollywood budgets to get off the ground. However every game developed is a moonshot worth millions of dollars that could be wasted if there are no sales to prop it up.

This risk however is very worthwhile. Currently, the video game industry is large than both the music and movie industry combined, while having immense potential for growth. It is estimated that there are around 2 billion people in the world who buy and play video games. That is nearly 1 out of every 4 people. Video games being a software product makes it very easy to scale and ship world wide, compared to other industries which may be stricted to their regions due to industry contraints.

Analyzing video game sales data can provide valuable insights into what drives people to buying a certain video game. By analzying infomation about sales from video games, game developers and publishers can make informed decisions about what makes a game attractive for their development of their titles, ensuring that each moonshot they make will hopefully hit its target.

So let us determine what exactly makes a video game sell well.

1. Data Collection¶

To start with, we need to collect our data about video game sales. We are using a website called vgcharz that has data on thousands of video game titles, their sales, their ratings, etc. VGChartz is a website that provides video game sales data and related information to video game industry professionals, analysts, and enthusiasts. They collect data from various sources, including publishers, retailers, and consumers, and provide information on game sales, release dates, platforms, genres, and more. VGChartz is often used by video game industry professionals to track market trends, analyze sales data, and make business decisions.

Due to the large volume of data needed to be scraped, I am using a python framework called Scrapy to scrape information from the website, and write it in as CSV file. This program was ran seperately to save resources and time, but the most meaningful part of the implementation is shown below. Scrapy allows for minimal code writing, saves resources, and pretty much allows one to basically run it in the background. All one has to do is write the rules and Scrapy will use a 'spider' that will asychronously gather the data you want. For more infomation about using Scrapy for yourself visit: https://docs.scrapy.org/en/latest/intro/overview.html

In [ ]:
from scrapy import Request, Spider


def strip(value):
    return value.strip() if isinstance(value, str) else value


class GameStatisticsSpider(Spider):
    name = "game_statistics"

    def __init__(self, name=None, **kwargs):
        super().__init__(name, **kwargs)
        self.pages = int(kwargs.get("pages", 10))
    
    #aschronously sends a get request
    def start_requests(self):
        for i in range(1, self.pages + 1):
            yield Request(f"https://www.vgchartz.com/games/games.php?page={i}&order=Sales&ownership=Both&direction=DESC&showtotalsales=1&shownasales=1&showpalsales=1&showjapansales=1&showothersales=1&showpublisher=1&showdeveloper=1&showreleasedate=1&showlastupdate=1&showvgchartzscore=1&showcriticscore=1&showuserscore=1&showshipped=1")
    
    #parses out the html response into the data we want
    def parse(self, response):
            for game in response.xpath(".//div[@id='generalBody']/table/tr"):       
                title = self.get_title(game)
                if title is None:
                    continue  # None-titles are column headers or the footer row
                
                yield {
                    "pos": strip(game.xpath(".//td[1]/text()").get()),
                    "title": title,
                    "platform": strip(game.xpath(".//td[4]/img/@alt").get()),
                    "publisher": strip(game.xpath(".//td[5]/text()").get()),
                    "developer": strip(game.xpath(".//td[6]/text()").get()),
                    "vgchartz_score": strip(game.xpath(".//td[7]/text()").get()),
                    "critic_score": strip(game.xpath(".//td[8]/text()").get()),
                    "user_score": strip(game.xpath(".//td[9]/text()").get()),
                    "total_shipped": strip(game.xpath(".//td[10]/text()").get()),
                    "total_sales": strip(game.xpath(".//td[11]/text()").get()),
                    "na_sales": strip(game.xpath(".//td[12]/text()").get()),
                    "pal_sales": strip(game.xpath(".//td[13]/text()").get()),
                    "japan_sales": strip(game.xpath(".//td[14]/text()").get()),
                    "other_sales": strip(game.xpath(".//td[15]/text()").get()),
                    "release_date": strip(game.xpath(".//td[16]/text()").get()),
                    "last_update": strip(game.xpath(".//td[17]/text()").get()),
                }
 
  #returns the title of our game
    def get_title(self, game):
        title = game.xpath(".//td[3]/a/text()").get()
        return title.strip() if isinstance(title, str) else title

From this point on, we will be using the CSV file produced from running Scrapy.

We will be going with the second option. We want to determine what drives video game sales, and missing data will not help us reach that conclusion.

Let us determine if the ratings affect if a game sells well or not. In the seaborn library, we will be using a joinplot. It is a plot which combines scatter plot and histogram plots to give us the information about the bivariate distribution of two variables along with the univariate distribution of each variable. It can also include a regression line, a kernel density estimation, and a Pearson correlation coefficient. This type of plot is useful to explore the relationship between two variables, especially in large datasets.

3. Analysis with Linear Regression and Hypothesis Testing¶

In Part 2 we have determined some factors may affect video game sales. In this part we will create a model with these factors and see whether or model itself is statistically significant when it comes to predicting sales with these factors.

But first let us double check to see if our factors have a strong or weak relationship with sales.

To determine this, we can use linear regression and calculate the R-value, which measures how strong a relationship is between two variables. We will use hypothesis testing to see whether or not that result we get is significant. Our null hypothesis is an assumption about the data we assume to be true unless proven otherwise. In this case our null hypothesis is that we assume community interaction has no correlation with global sales. The alternative hypothesis is the assumption that the opposite is true. This is only true if our null hypothesis is rejected. In our case the AH is that community interaction and global sales are indeed correlated. To determine whether or not the null hypothesis should be rejected, we must calculate the p-value, which is a value that determine whether or not the null hypothesis is rejected.

To prove that community interaction is indeed related to sales, we will be using linear regression to do so. Using the scipy library, we can create a linear regression model that will do all the math and calulate our r value and p value for us! We will use the critic count and user count to represent community interaction.

In [ ]:
from scipy import stats

# convert User_Score to a numerical data type
dropped['Critic_Count'] = pd.to_numeric(dropped['Critic_Count'], errors='coerce')

# drop rows with missing values
dropped = dropped.dropna(subset=['Critic_Count', 'Global_Sales'])

# create a scatter plot of global sales vs. Critic scores
sns.scatterplot(x='Critic_Count', y='Global_Sales', data=dropped)

# perform a linear regression
regression = stats.linregress(dropped['Critic_Count'], dropped['Global_Sales'])
slope = regression.slope
intercept = regression.intercept
rvalue = regression.rvalue
pvalue = regression.pvalue
stderr = regression.stderr

# plot the regression line
sns.lineplot(x=dropped['Critic_Count'], y=slope * dropped['Critic_Count'] + intercept, color='red')

# print the regression results
print(f"Slope: {slope:.2f}")
print(f"Intercept: {intercept:.2f}")
print(f"R-value: {rvalue:.2f}")
print(f"P-value: {pvalue:.2f}")
print(f"Standard Error: {stderr:.2f}")

# drop rows with missing values
dropped = dropped.dropna(subset=['User_Count', 'Global_Sales'])

# create a scatter plot of global sales vs. user scores
sns.scatterplot(x='User_Count', y='Global_Sales', data=dropped)

# perform a linear regression
regression = stats.linregress(dropped['User_Count'], dropped['Global_Sales'])
slope = regression.slope
intercept = regression.intercept
rvalue = regression.rvalue
pvalue = regression.pvalue
stderr = regression.stderr

# plot the regression line
sns.lineplot(x=dropped['User_Count'], y=slope * dropped['User_Count'] + intercept, color='red')

# print the regression results
print(f"Slope: {slope:.2f}")
print(f"Intercept: {intercept:.2f}")
print(f"R-value: {rvalue:.2f}")
print(f"P-value: {pvalue:.2f}")
print(f"Standard Error: {stderr:.2f}")

As you can see our p-value is 0, meaning we are able to reject the null hypothesis since it is lower than 0.05 which is our signifcance level. This means that interaction and sales are indeed correlated and have a relationship. The R-value of 0.29 suggests that the correlation is weak.

Next, let us create a linear regression model with the rest of our discrete factors, that is factors that are not numeric. In our case that is Devlopers, Publishers, Platform and Genre. We have shown that these discrete factors influence the sales of video games somewhat in part 2. With these terms added, we can improve how well our model fits and can predict the sales of a video game.

We will be using the sklearn library so that we can train our model and get an R squared value using a transformer. An R squared value shows how well the model fits and can accurately predict the variation in the data. This means that the model can explain if the variation comes from the data itself or elsewhere (which is not good). I will split the models into four as we can predict our regional sales for a better fit as regions were a discrete variable and global sales are just the sum of the four regions.

In [ ]:
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# load the data
df = dropped

# define the feature and target variables
X = df.drop(['Global_Sales', 'NA_Sales', 'EU_Sales', 'JP_Sales', 'Other_Sales'], axis=1)
y_na = df['NA_Sales']
y_eu = df['EU_Sales']
y_jp = df['JP_Sales']
y_other = df['Other_Sales']

# split the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_na_train, y_na_test, y_eu_train, y_eu_test, y_jp_train, y_jp_test, y_other_train, y_other_test = train_test_split(
    X, y_na, y_eu, y_jp, y_other, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# define the preprocessing steps
numeric_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('scaler', StandardScaler())
])

categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('onehot', OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore'))
])

preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', numeric_transformer, ['Year_of_Release','User_Count', 'Critic_Count']), #continuous terms
        ('cat', categorical_transformer, ['Platform', 'Genre', 'Publisher', 'Developer']) #discrete terms
    ])

# define the pipelines with linear regression model
pipeline_na = Pipeline(steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor),
                              ('regressor', LinearRegression())])

pipeline_eu = Pipeline(steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor),
                              ('regressor', LinearRegression())])

pipeline_jp = Pipeline(steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor),
                              ('regressor', LinearRegression())])

pipeline_other = Pipeline(steps=[('preprocessor', preprocessor),
                                 ('regressor', LinearRegression())])

# fit the pipelines to the training data
pipeline_na.fit(X_train, y_na_train)
pipeline_eu.fit(X_train, y_eu_train)
pipeline_jp.fit(X_train, y_jp_train)
pipeline_other.fit(X_train, y_other_train)

# make predictions on the testing data
y_na_pred = pipeline_na.predict(X_test)
y_eu_pred = pipeline_eu.predict(X_test)
y_jp_pred = pipeline_jp.predict(X_test)
y_other_pred = pipeline_other.predict(X_test)

# evaluate the models on the testing data
score_na = pipeline_na.score(X_test, y_na_test)
score_eu = pipeline_eu.score(X_test, y_eu_test)
score_jp = pipeline_jp.score(X_test, y_jp_test)
score_other = pipeline_other.score(X_test, y_other_test)

print(f"R-squared score for NA sales: {score_na:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared score for EU sales: {score_eu:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared score for JP sales: {score_jp:.2f}")
print(f"R-squared score for Other sales: {score_other:.2f}")

R-squared score for NA sales: 0.36
R-squared score for EU sales: 0.36
R-squared score for JP sales: 0.34
R-squared score for Other sales: 0.23

As you can see, we were able to improve our model somewhat and determined that the terms/factors we had chosen were weakly able to predict the game sales as long as you had the terms/predictors.

Conclusion¶

Unfortunetly, due to missing data, we were only able to find some factors that could weakly determine how much a game would sell. In the gaming industry where a game cost millions of dollars to make, it is very important to determine whether or not that particular game would be worth investing in since how much profit a game makes determine whether or not that games gets developed. Scraping the data took most of my time, and it was difficult to find relevant infomation from reputable sources since the industry often does not disclose things like the marketing budget, which would have been useful for this project. Additonally, the lack of infomation I could obtain about each video game really limited me in what I could explore. Nonethless, we can determine that the Genre, Region, Publisher, Platform, and Interactions by the gaming community (critic and user count) all contribute into what determines if a game sells well.

Conversely this also means that stuff like User and Critic scores are not much of a factor that impacts sales. With this infomation, what established companies and developers can do instead is cut things that would increase scores to lower the bar for profit, or reapproriate them into another area that can affect sales, like marketing.
